Town of Winchester, MA
August 20 at 9:08 PM ·

WINCHESTER HEALTH DEPARTMENT'S DIGITAL DOSE:

FLU CLINICS: Public and school-based clinics will be held in Winchester. Details coming soon!

FluMist and Shots, including High-dose for seniors will be available. The flu vaccine is now required by December 31st 2020 for all children six months of age or older who are attending child care, pre-school, kindergarten, K-12, and colleges and universities in Massachusetts. There is no change in CDC’s recommendation on timing of vaccination this flu season. Getting vaccinated in July or August is too early, especially for older people, because of the likelihood of reduced protection against flu infection later in the flu season. September and October are good times to get vaccinated. To learn more go to: cdc.gov/flu/index.htm. Winchester flu clinic dates will be posted here when available: winchester.us/556/Vaccination-Clinics

August 7 at 1:14 PM ·

THE WINCHESTER HEALTH DEPARTMENT'S DIGITAL DOSE
There are many different types of COVID-19 tests and they are not all equal. The Winchester Health Department recommends the PCR (Polymerase Chain Reaction) Viral Test to see if you have a current infection. This is required for travel orders and may be required when testing is needed for school purposes. Before going to any testing site check their website or call ahead to determine the type of test they are offering, your cost and the results turnaround time (which can vary depending on the local and national testing demand at that point in time). For more information on testing locations and different types of testing check out: https://www.winchester.us/633/Covid-Testing

post_text:
July 29, 2020 Press Release

After two meetings and more than three hours of listening to public comment, the Winchester School Committee debated and unanimously passed the following two motions during their School Committee meeting on July 28.

MOTION 1
The Winchester Public Schools shall no longer appropriate names, images or practices from American Indian/Alaska Native cultures or specific American Indian/Alaska Native tribes, including for any team name, logo or mascot.

MOTION 2
The Superintendent of Schools shall develop for School Committee review a transition plan for a new Winchester High School logo and/or mascot, including scope, costs and timeline. The plan shall be inclusive of the school and parent community and honor the achievements of our students, both past and present.

The Winchester Public Schools and the School Committee look forward to a respectful and inclusive transition over the coming weeks and months.
text:
July 29, 2020 Press Release

After two meetings and more than three hours of listening to public comment, the Winchester School Committee debated and unanimously passed the following two motions during their School Committee meeting on July 28.

MOTION 1
The Winchester Public Schools shall no longer appropriate names, images or practices from American Indian/Alaska Native cultures or specific American Indian/Alaska Native tribes, including for any team name, logo or mascot.

MOTION 2
The Superintendent of Schools shall develop for School Committee review a transition plan for a new Winchester High School logo and/or mascot, including scope, costs and timeline. The plan shall be inclusive of the school and parent community and honor the achievements of our students, both past and present.

The Winchester Public Schools and the School Committee look forward to a respectful and inclusive transition over the coming weeks and months.

Calling all coders! fEmpower is an introductory computer science course for girls grades 3-5. The curriculum is taught on Zoom by a team of three WHS seniors who have extensive programming experience from AP Computer Science to Technovation. The course utilizes Scratch, Java, and various other programming tools to cover an array of topics, with no prior experience necessary. The class is completely free of charge, and has been piloted at Vinson Owen Elementary.

DATES: 6 classes from 10:00-11:00 AM, Mondays/Wednesdays/Fridays over August 3rd-14th.
SIGN UP here: https://forms.gle/WTxzupWX6njHoakf9

The Tank wraps up today, Monday, at 3pm.





Which team of student entrepreneurs will be victorious in WFEE’s Venture Competition?

Our finalists are :

fEmpower: Juliet Jiang, Dhwani Sreenivas, Elysia Yuan
Pocket Pharm: Yanjie (Jack) Guo, Allan Huang , Alex Sun
TeachMe: Shrivas Raghavan
The Third Eye: Kenny Xu and Arthur Zhang

WinCam will stream the pitches live, our panel of judges will weigh in and our students will quickly know which business ideas can move forward.

The competition is an outgrowth of WFEE’s Student Innovation grants, making learning more engaging with real world projects.

Got some time on your hands? Want to learn something new? The National Honor Society is banding together to share their skills with our community in free one-on-one sessions, during which participants can learn and virtually practice new skills with an NHS member. From art to language, from technology to music, they hope that you will take advantage of these opportunities and challenge yourself in a new way.
This opportunity is open to ANYONE who is interested. All are encouraged to participate, regardless of age, skill level or experience! Click here to see what kinds of lessons are offered: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Rkf5ZOep5BKaliHRz-esWgedCcDup7zO_CMK10tFxow/edit

Winchester High School Seniors: Every Friday for the rest of the school year, at exactly 8:20 PM we will be lighting our athletic fields, specifically Knowlton Stadium and Ciarcia Field, to let our seniors know we have not forgotten about you! We are“keeping a light on for you.”

Please consider driving by any Friday night at 8:20 pm or taking a distance-respecting walk/jog to see the fields lit up in your honor. The fields will be lit for 20 minutes, at 8:20 PM, as a symbolic gesture from the WHS staff and our community partners to the class of 2020. You have not been forgotten!

post_text:
From Wright Locke Farm:

Design the Farm's New Weathervane!

With everyone looking for home-based activities, we thought that this could be a great time to ask for your help to design an important piece of the Farm landscape. Our new All Seasons Barn will have a weathervane and we would love some ideas from the community! You may be familiar with the 1827 Barn's classic horse weathervane (above) - an homage to the Lockes' horses and the Farm's past. We are looking for ideas from the community as to what to put up on this new barn -- something that symbolizes the farm as it is now: community-centric, educational, organic.

Design specifications:
- Should have a clear "point" that indicates wind direction
- Easy to fabricate out of metal
- Should be easily seen and understood from 50 ft away
- No larger than 3x3 ft in dimension
- Sent to info@wlfarm.org by April 30th
- Can be scanned in sketch, pdf, or other digital format

We will assemble a panel made up of engaged farm community members to decide which design will be immortalized at the farm for years to come. Let the creativity begin!

With everyone looking for home-based activities, we thought that this could be a great time to ask for your help to design an important piece of the Farm landscape. Our new All Seasons Barn will have a weathervane and we would love some ideas from the community! You may be familiar with the 1827 Barn's classic horse weathervane (above) - an homage to the Lockes' horses and the Farm's past. We are looking for ideas from the community as to what to put up on this new barn -- something that symbolizes the farm as it is now: community-centric, educational, organic.

Design specifications:
- Should have a clear "point" that indicates wind direction
- Easy to fabricate out of metal
- Should be easily seen and understood from 50 ft away
- No larger than 3x3 ft in dimension
- Sent to info@wlfarm.org by April 30th
- Can be scanned in sketch, pdf, or other digital format

We will assemble a panel made up of engaged farm community members to decide which design will be immortalized at the farm for years to come. Let the creativity begin!

Lahey Health would love to see Winchester students and their families make "Thank You" and appreciation cards for health care workers at Winchester Hospital. This is a wonderful way for students of all ages, and parents, to give back to people on the "front lines" in our community. A sample card is posted below.

Here are the instructions:

- Make cards out of 8 1/2" X 11" paper folded, or smaller
- Card makers can sign their first names and their school
- Cards should be dropped off in the marked bin outside the front doors of Winchester High School. The bin will be there between 9 am Wednesday, April 15th to 3 pm Friday, April 17th.
- The paper cards will be aired out before being delivered, so it is important that only paper cards are deposited in the bin.
- For the health and safety of our custodial staff and administrators, please do not try to enter the high school, and do not leave anything if there is no bin.
- If you miss the collection times and would still like to contribute, contact Anne Marie Edenhofner at aedenhofner@winchesterps.org.

FAN NEIGHBORHOOD WALK ART SHOW

When: Friday, April 10 and Saturday, April 11 (rain date on Monday, April 13th)
Where: Sidewalks of Winchester

Calling artists of all ages and abilities! FAN wants to embrace our community while supporting our efforts to keep each other safe and stay separate at this time.

Let's create something beautiful and put on a town-wide art show!

Everyone is encouraged to post their artwork of all types - in front yards, in street-facing windows, or anywhere visible from the sidewalk for all to enjoy on their strolls around town on Friday, April 10 and Saturday, April 11 (rain date on Monday, April 13th). Viewers are encouraged to bring a piece of sidewalk chalk on their walk and leave positive messages to let the artists know that their work was spotted and appreciated!

Please be mindful of social distancing while walking and stopping to observe.

post_text:
Governor Baker just announced school closures will continue until 5/4/20 at the earliest. More details from state education officials will follow tomorrow..

Let's all take a deep breath! Students, teachers, staff members, and parents are already doing excellent work in the new normal. This lengthy closure will lead some families to advocate for a quick move to more structured academics, but please be patient as we work to meet the complex needs of our nearly 5,000 students, over 800 of whom have identified disabilities. Families have been sent a link to a feedback survey. Teachers will also ask students for informal feedback about what is working well for them and what they would like to see in the future. Please continue to share your kind words and maintain your faith in us. We vow to come out stronger and more successful than we started this school year as we take risks, learn, and grow together.

-Avoid playgrounds.
-Limit visits to stores/restaurants/coffee shops.
-Prepare food at home if possible.

post_text: Next Tuesday, March 10, from noon to 1:30 pm, in the Waterfield Room (Town Hall, Lower Level), Jon Mattleman will be hosting the latest Winchester Coalition Lunch and Learn speaker: Bringing light to suicide- helping community members respond to suicidal statements and actions. This engaging talk will teach community members the Q.P.R. (Question, Persuade, Refer) approach to supporting someone presenting with suicidal statements and/or behavior. The saying "It takes a village" could not be more accurate when speaking about how to support other community members and our youth, and this training will make sure we all have more tools in our toolboxes.

post_text: PRESCHOOL LOTTERY APPLICATIONS DUE BY JANUARY 31st: The Winchester Integrated Preschool currently located within the Lynch Elementary and Vinson-Owen Elementary School is now accepting applications for the 2020-2021 school year. At this time, applications are being accepted for the lottery process through January 31, 2020. Please visit our website at Winchester Integrated Preschool to sign up for a tour, learn about our application process, and to print an application. Please email scasey@winchesterps.org with any questions.

post_text: We are delighted to announce that the Lynch School was invited by the Massachusetts School Building Authority into the eligibility phase for a new building today. We hope to be opening a new Lynch School in 5-7 years, but are excited about this first phase of the project. Many thanks to the Select Board, EFPBC, school committee, and town officials for great support.
text: We are delighted to announce that the Lynch School was invited by the Massachusetts School Building Authority into the eligibility phase for a new building today. We hope to be opening a new Lynch School in 5-7 years, but are excited about this first phase of the project. Many thanks to the Select Board, EFPBC, school committee, and town officials for great support.
